The institution osa servus alienus is at first sight enigmatical, for as he could acquire the inheritance only for his master, why not institute the latter at once? The solution is twofold. Firstly, the institution of the slave secured the transmission of the inheritance to the heirs of his master, whereas if the latter had been instituted himself and had pre· deceased the testator, the institution would have lapsed: and this could not be prevented by giving a ‘ remainder ' to his heire-by substitution, for they were incertae personae; nemo est heres viventis.
